{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}} {{Infobox ancient site | name = Aiadava | native_name = | native_name_lang = | alternate_name = ''Aiadaba'', ''Aeadaba'' | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | map_type = Serbia | map_alt = | map_caption = | map_size = | altitude_m = | altitude_ref = | relief = | coordinates = {{coord|43.2180|22.3074|display=inline,title}} | map_dot_label = | location = [[Bela Palanka]],&#8203;&nbsp;[[Serbia]] | area = | built = | abandoned = | epochs = <!-- actually displays as "Periods" --> | cultures = | event = | discovered = | excavations = | archaeologists = | condition = | designation1 = | designation1_number = | designation2 = | designation2_number = | website = | architectural_styles = | architectural_details = | notes = }}
'''Aiadava''' (''Aiadaba'' or ''Aeadaba'', {{lang-gr|Αἰάδαβα}}<ref>*''Procopii Caesariensis opera omnia''. Edited by J. Haury; revised by G. Wirth. 3 vols. Leipzig: [[Teubner]], 1976-64. Greek text. </ref>) was a [[Dacians|Dacian]] town in the [[Remesiana]] region,<ref name="Olteanu_Toponyms">{{cite web|url=http://soltdm.com/geo/arts/categs/categs.htm |title=Linguae Thraco-Daco-Moesorum - Toponyms Section |author=Olteanu, Sorin |language=Romanian |work=Linguae Thraco-Daco-Moesorum |accessdate=2 December 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vSjj8iYr?url=http://soltdm.com/geo/arts/categs/categs.htm |archivedate=3 January 2011 }}</ref> present day [[Bela Palanka]], [[Serbia]].
After the Romans conquered [[Moesia]] in the 75 BC, the new castrum (imperial domain with estates) and municipium was known initially as ''Ulpianorum'' and then ''Remesiana'' ([[Moesi]]) and laid on the [[Via Militaris]] road, between [[Naissus]] and [[Serdica]].
Emperor [[Justinian]] (r. 527–565) had following strongholds in the district of Remesiana:
{| class="wikitable" | Brittura Subaras Lamponiana Stronges Dalmatas Primiana Phrerraria Topera Tomes Cuas Tzertzenutzas Stens '''Aeadaba''' Destreba Pretzouries Cumudeba Deurias Lutzolo Rhepordenes Spelonca Scumbro Briparo Tulcoburgo Longiana Lupophantana [[Dardapara]] Burdomina Grinciapana Graecus Drasimarca |}
The [[patron saint]] of [[Romania]], [[Nicetas of Remesiana]], was a 4th-century [[bishop]] at Remesiana, of possible [[Dacians|Dacian]] descent.<ref>[http://www.bvau.ro/docs/doc_eng.htm The Romanian People - Continuer of the European Neolithic Civilization]</ref>
Excavations include well-preserved castrum dating to 4th century, a hoard of 260 coins minted during the rule of [[Constantine I]], [[Theodosius I]], [[Tiberius Claudius Nero]] (3rd century AD).<ref>Ancient diseases: the elements of palaeopathology-Srboljub Živanović 1982 </ref>
<gallery> File:BelaPalankaIskopine.jpg|Basilica Apse under excavation in Remesiana. Basilica is found under modern residential building. File:Bela Palanka Sept Sev.jpg|3rd century [[Septimius Severus]] monument in Bela Palanka. </gallery>
